<DOC><DOCNO> AP890216-0088 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1146EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-ArabAlliance     02-16 0217</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Arab Alliance,0222</SECOND><HEAD>Four Arab Nations Sign Accord to Form Economic Alliance</HEAD><DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The leaders of Egypt, Iraq, Jordan and NorthYemen signed an accord today to create an economic alliance designedto boost Arab unity, an official report said.   Officials of the four countries say the new alliance is aimedsolely at cementing economic ties _ not at rivaling the Arab Leagueas a political bloc.   The Iraqi News Agency said the pact was signed at a summitmeeting hosted by President Saddam Hussein. The meeting was attendedby King Hussein of Jordan; President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt; andPresident Ali Abdullah Saleh of North Yemen.   Recent press reports have speculated the new group, called theArab Cooperation Council, is meant to counter the influence of SaudiArabia.   But Saudi King Fahd called the Iraqi president by telephone tocongratulate him and the three other leaders on forming the group,the agency said.   The main goal of the Arab Cooperation Council is to achieve``cooperation, coordination, integration and solidarity'' among thesignatories, the agency said. The group's charter envisagescooperation in agriculture, industry, culture and social programs.The charter also calls for working toward an Arab common market, thereport said.   The new group will have a general secretariat in Amman, Jordan.</TEXT></DOC>